### Currying vs Partial Application

**Currying** transforms a function `f(a, b, c)` into `f(a)(b)(c)` — a chain of single-argument functions. Each call returns a new function until all arguments are collected.

**Partial application** fixes some arguments of a function upfront and returns a new function waiting for the rest. Unlike currying, partial application can fix multiple args at once.

```javascript
// curry implementation
function curry(fn) {
  return function curried(...args) {
    if (args.length >= fn.length) {
      return fn.apply(this, args);
    }
    return function(...moreArgs) {
      return curried.apply(this, args.concat(moreArgs));
    };
  };
}

// Usage
const add = curry((a, b, c) => a + b + c);
console.log(add(1)(2)(3));    // 6
console.log(add(1, 2)(3));    // 6 — also works
console.log(add(1)(2, 3));    // 6 — also works

// Partial application (different from currying)
const multiply = (a, b, c) => a * b * c;
const double = multiply.bind(null, 2);     // fixes first arg
const doubleThenTriple = multiply.bind(null, 2, 3); // fixes two args
console.log(double(3, 4));         // 24
console.log(doubleThenTriple(5));  // 30
```

**Practical use cases:**

```javascript
// Point-free pipeline with curried helpers
const prop = curry((key, obj) => obj[key]);
const gt = curry((threshold, val) => val > threshold);

const users = [{ name: 'Alice', age: 30 }, { name: 'Bob', age: 17 }];
const getAge = prop('age');
const isAdult = gt(17);

const adults = users.filter(u => isAdult(getAge(u)));
console.log(adults.map(prop('name'))); // ['Alice']

// Curried logger
const log = curry((level, msg) => console.log(`[${level}] ${msg}`));
const warn = log('WARN');
const error = log('ERROR');
warn('something off');   // [WARN] something off
error('critical fail');  // [ERROR] critical fail
```

**Common trap:** Currying only works reliably on functions with a fixed arity (`fn.length`). Rest parameters (`...args`) have `length = 0`, breaking the auto-curry mechanism.

**Частая ошибка:** Каррирование работает надёжно только для функций с фиксированной арностью (`fn.length`). Rest-параметры (`...args`) дают `length = 0`, что ломает механизм авто-каррирования.

